        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Vineland, N.J.</placeName>
                    <date>Feb. 11, 1875.</date>
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Darwin,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Some weeks ago I obtained from the ponds, simply, the long white stims of <hi rend="underline">Utricularia</hi>.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Freezing had divested them of all leaf stems. Very soon the new branches began to make their appearance, and I found, that the species that I am observing, is perfectly circinate—when the branch is wholly unrolled that is the end of its growth. These branches send off secondary branches, and then again divide and sub-divide, and with the bladders scattered among the leaves and branches, it takes but a little stretch of the imagination to make this plant equal the animal vascular system.</p>
<p>Look at some of the flukes—for instance, <hi rend="underline">Amphistoma conicum</hi>,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> the vascular system of which, under the microscope, looks very much as this plant appears to the naked eye.</p>
<p>Yours gratefully | Mary Treat.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Treat had sent CD her initial observations on <hi rend="italic">Utricularia</hi> (bladderwort) in a letter of 2 December 1874 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 22).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><hi rend="italic">Amphistoma conicum</hi> (now <hi rend="italic">Paramphistomum cervi</hi>, rumen fluke) is a parasitic flatworm that infects ruminants such as sheep and cattle.</note>
        </div>        
            
